		<part id="api-effect">
			<title>The API Effect</title>
			<slide id="language-promise">
				<title>APIs are <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wDYeU2T4v2o&amp;list=UUDD75qoXHJSz4pv0o3WcTUw">Languages</a> and <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gFu7CQKmBeQ&amp;list=UUDD75qoXHJSz4pv0o3WcTUw">Promises</a> (for Machines)</title>
				<img src="robots.png" title="Chatting Robots" style="float: right ; width : 25% ; margin : 5% ; "/>
				<ul>
					<li><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wDYeU2T4v2o&amp;list=UUDD75qoXHJSz4pv0o3WcTUw">An API is a Language</a></li>
					<ul>
						<li>Two applications can communicate (within or across organizational boundaries)</li>
						<li>Other applications can start using it because the language is well-defined</li>
					</ul>
					<li><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gFu7CQKmBeQ&amp;list=UUDD75qoXHJSz4pv0o3WcTUw">An API is a Promise</a></li>
					<ul>
						<li>A promise to provide services for programmatic access</li>
						<li>A promise to keep the language stable for as long as possible</li>
					</ul>
				</ul>
			</slide>
